## Scope

This slice owns the construction layer on top of Part A's contract: composing an end-to-end optical train from palette elements and routing the reflected/transmitted outputs of every element into a branching beam tree, driving the reused single-system solver per node. It also owns the structural editors over the reused stack types — the visual stack/layer editor, incident/exit medium selectors, and the substrate-type switch — the per-element default-unit hook, the JSON-canonical serialization of the beam tree (field-level `$defs`), the construction page's operator UX, and the [Standard] gradient-index auto-discretization. Construction here is purely topological and structural; curved elements (Part C / slice 004), optimization, charting, materials/dispersion editing, sources, and persistence machinery are out of scope.

## Requirements

The following are the parent's Part B directives, reproduced verbatim. Contractful identifiers and `<file>:<line>` references are preserved exactly.

### R-1 (B.1) Beam-tree construction MUST drive the reused single-system solver per node, never fork it

`OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` MUST evaluate each `BeamNode` by calling the reused engine solver `OpticalSystemSolver(info, system, parameters)` (`Solvers.fs:199`) on that node's `OpticalSystem` and incident light, then read its `Solution.emSys` (`Solvers.fs:156`) to obtain the `EmFieldSystem` whose `reflected` and `transmitted` `EmField`s feed the node's two branches (`Fields.fs:550`). The solver, its `BaseOpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:115`), and `SolverParameters.numberOfReflections` (`Solvers.fs:15`) MUST NOT be forked, re-derived, or shadowed (Part A constraint 2). The node's solver inputs — `IncidentLightInfo` for a root node (`Fields.fs:338`) or an incident `EmField` produced by the parent (see §B.4) — are stored on the `BeamNode` per Part A §A.4.

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `OpticalSystemSolver` `Solvers.fs:199` — the only entry point for solving one element/system; returns a `Solution`.
- `Solution.emSys` `Solvers.fs:156` — collapses `Single`/`Multiple` into one `EmFieldSystem` with `incident`/`reflected`/`transmitted`.
- `SolverParameters.defaultValue` `Solvers.fs:21` — supplies `numberOfReflections = 3` unless a node overrides it.

Scope exclusion: Part B MUST NOT add a solver cache, a memoization layer, or a retry/error-wrapping shim around the solver; live recalculation and busy/cancel ([Standard], 010 §1) are owned by the UI part, not by the domain solver loop.

### R-2 (B.2) The `BeamTree`/`BeamNode`/`BeamBranch` topology MUST be the NET-NEW orchestration carrier defined in Part A §A.4 [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` MUST place the `BeamTree`, `BeamNode`, and `BeamBranch` definitions from Part A §A.4 in a new module `OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new). Per Part A: `BeamBranch = Reflected | Transmitted`; a `BeamNode` carries its `ConstructorElement`, its `OpticalSystem`, its solver inputs, and up to two child attachments keyed by `BeamBranch`. This is a NET-NEW topology with no Berreman equivalent and MUST be expressed as F# records and discriminated unions (Part A constraint 1). The child attachment MUST be modelled as a `Map<BeamBranch, BeamNode>` (or equivalent immutable two-slot record), so that a non-mirror node MAY hold a `Reflected` child, a `Transmitted` child, both, or neither, and a mirror node holds at most the `Reflected` key (§B.3). Immutable F# structures MUST be used throughout (Part A constraint 1; CLAUDE.md code style).

This realizes 010 §1's [Core] "Branching beam paths (reflected & transmitted) — a system tree, not just a chain": every non-mirror element exposes two attachment points and downstream sub-systems attach to each branch independently. A linear chain (source → polarizer → sample → analyzer → detector) is the degenerate case where each node attaches a single child on the `Transmitted` branch.

Scope exclusion: no schema versioning, no migration code, and no backwards-compat shim for the tree shape; the `beamNode`/`beamBranch` `$defs` are owned by Part A §A.7 and filled field-level here (§B.9), not re-versioned.

### R-3 (B.3) Mirror nodes MUST carry the `Reflected` branch ONLY [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) MUST enforce that a `BeamNode` whose `ConstructorElement` is a mirror (`FlatMirror`, and — owned by Part C — `CurvedMirror`; the `ConstructorElement` DU is Part A §A.4) admits at most a `Reflected` child attachment and MUST reject (or structurally make unrepresentable) any `Transmitted` attachment, by design ignoring transmitted light even where it physically leaks. A smart constructor `BeamNode.attach (branch : BeamBranch) (child : BeamNode) (parent : BeamNode) : Result<BeamNode, BeamTreeError>` MUST return an error value when `branch = Transmitted` and the parent is a mirror; `Result<'T,'E>` MUST be used for this validation, not exceptions (CLAUDE.md code style). `BeamTreeError` is a NET-NEW DU defined in the same module, traced to this directive.

This realizes 010 §1's [Core] "Mirrors are a deliberate special case … the reflected branch only … Only the reflected output can carry downstream elements." Part B classifies `FlatMirror` only; the curved-mirror element and its local-interface physics are OUT OF SCOPE here and owned by Part C.

### R-4 (B.4) Inter-element beam routing MUST use the reused `EmField.propagate` seam [Core]

When a `BeamNode` attaches a child on branch `b`, `OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) MUST take the corresponding `EmField` from the parent's solved `EmFieldSystem` — `reflected` for `Reflected`, `transmitted` for `Transmitted` (`Fields.fs:552-554`) — and use it as the incident field driving the child's solve, propagating it across any intervening element/gap through the reused seam `EmField.propagate (s : Layer) : EmField` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`). The child node MUST then be solved through the `EmField`-based path already provided by the engine: `BaseOpticalSystemSolver(emf : EmField, system : ShortOpticalSystem)` (`Solvers.fs:149`), where `ShortOpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:56`) carries the child's `films` and `lower`. The energy/polarization carried along the branch is exactly the field state inside the propagated `EmField` (its `emComponents`, `Fields.fs:427`); Part B MUST NOT introduce a separate Jones/Stokes accumulator — Stokes/ellipticity/azimuth read-outs are computed by the field-function seam owned elsewhere (Part A engine seams, `FieldFunctions.fs`).

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `EmField.propagate` `BerremanMatrix.fs:224` — the single inter-element propagation seam; advances an `EmField` across a `Layer`.
- `BaseOpticalSystemSolver(emf, system)` `Solvers.fs:149` — the `EmField`-driven solver overload for a downstream node.
- `ShortOpticalSystem` `Media.fs:56` — the films-plus-lower system a downstream `EmField` is solved against.

Scope exclusion: Part B routes flat-element beams along the boundary normal only; off-axis ray direction, focusing, and beam-waist propagation are OUT OF SCOPE (owned by Part C). No incoherent-layer averaging here ([Standard], 010 §3, owned by the sources part).

### R-5 (B.5) The visual stack/layer editor MUST operate on the reused `Layer`/`OpticalSystem` records [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST provide a stack/layer editor whose rows are the reused `Layer` records of a node's `OpticalSystem.films : List<Layer>` (`Media.fs:98`), each row editing that layer's `thickness : Thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) and `properties : OpticalProperties` (`Media.fs:26`, the tensor record `MaterialProperties.fs:165`). The editor MUST support add, delete, reorder, duplicate, and group operations as pure transformations producing a new `films` list (immutable; Part A constraint 1), and the surrounding `OpticalSystem` MUST be rebuilt via record copy-and-update — never by mutating engine state. Layer-class/anisotropy and crystal-axis rotation controls ([Standard], 010 §1) MUST reuse the engine's `Layer.rotate` / `OpticalSystem.rotate` members (`Media.fs:30`, `Media.fs:120`) rather than re-deriving rotations.

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `OpticalSystem.films` `Media.fs:98` — the reused list the editor rows map to.
- `Thickness` DU `Media.fs:12` — the per-row thickness value (`Thickness of double<meter> | Infinity`); thickness is stored in meters (Part A canonical-units rule).
- `OpticalSystem.rotate` / `Layer.rotate` `Media.fs:120,30` — reuse for the [Standard] orientation controls; do not re-implement Euler rotation.

This realizes 010 §1's [Core] "Visual stack/layer editor — add, delete, reorder, duplicate, and group layers … edit thickness and material per row." The [Standard] repeat/period builder (010 §1) is NOT delivered by Part B; it is owned by Part J (§J.2).

### R-6 (B.6) Incident & exit medium selectors MUST set the reused `upper`/`lower` half-spaces [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST provide incident- and exit-medium selectors that set, respectively, the `OpticalSystem.upper` and `OpticalSystem.lower` `OpticalProperties` half-spaces of the edited system (`Media.fs:97,100`). Each selector MUST resolve to an `OpticalProperties` value (the reused tensor record, `MaterialProperties.fs:165`) either by refractive-index entry or by reference to a materials-library entry; the materials library and dispersion resolution are owned by other parts, so Part B MUST consume a resolved `OpticalProperties` and MUST NOT re-implement index→tensor construction. Setting a selector MUST produce a new `OpticalSystem` by record update, preserving `films` and `substrate`.

This realizes 010 §1's [Core] "Incident & exit medium selectors (upper/lower half-spaces) with refractive index or material reference."

### R-7 (B.7) The substrate-type switch MUST toggle the reused `Substrate` DU and route into existing multi-reflection handling [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST provide a substrate-type switch with exactly three states — thin film, thick plate, wedge — that sets `OpticalSystem.substrate : Substrate option` (`Media.fs:99`): thin film ⇒ `None`; plate ⇒ `Some (Plate layer)`; wedge ⇒ `Some (Wedge wedgeLayer)` exposing the `WedgeAngle` (`Media.fs:34,40`, `Fields.fs:328`). The switch MUST NOT change how multiple internal reflections are computed: that behaviour is already implemented in `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:201-230`), which branches on `system.substrate` and, for `Plate`/`Wedge`, iterates the reflected/transmitted steps using `EmField.propagate` (`Solvers.fs:209,222`); Part B MUST route into that existing path unchanged and MUST NOT fork it.

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `Substrate` DU `Media.fs:40` (`Plate of Layer | Wedge of WedgeLayer`) — the reused carrier the switch toggles.
- `OpticalSystem.substrate` `Media.fs:99` — the `option` field set by the switch.
- `OpticalSystemSolver` substrate branch `Solvers.fs:201-230` — the existing multi-reflection driver; reuse, do not reimplement.

This realizes 010 §1's [Core] "Substrate type switch: thin film vs. thick plate vs. wedge (with wedge angle), exposing the existing multi-reflection handling."

### R-8 (B.8) Each beam node, layer, and source MUST carry a per-element default-unit hook [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) and the `OpticalConstructorProject` aggregate (Part A §A.7) MUST attach a per-element default-unit field — a `UnitOfMeasure` value (the NET-NEW DU owned by Part D; schema `$def` `unitOfMeasure`, Part A §A.7) — to each `BeamNode`, each editor layer row, and each source/incident-light entry, recording the unit that element was created in / is most natural for it. Part B owns ONLY this hook: storing and surfacing the default unit so the editor can display a plate in mm, a film in nm, and a source in nm/µm/eV without the user converting by hand. The conversion behaviour itself — meters↔nm/µm/Å/mm, eV via `E[eV] = 1239.84 / λ[nm]`, cm⁻¹ — is owned by Part D and MUST NOT be implemented in Part B. Per Part A's canonical-units rule (constraint 3), the underlying physical quantities MUST remain stored in meters (`double<meter>`, `Constants.fs:6`; `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`); the default-unit hook is display metadata only and MUST NOT change any stored SI value.

This realizes 010 §1's [Core] "Per-element default unit of measure — each layer/element/source remembers and displays the unit natural to it … full unit behaviour in §2" (Part D).

### R-9 (B.9) The beam tree and constructed systems MUST serialize to the JSON-canonical project, never to `.binz`

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST serialize the `BeamTree`, its `BeamNode`s, their `OpticalSystem`s, and the per-element default-unit hooks into the JSON-canonical `OpticalConstructorProject` validated against `optical-constructor-project.schema.json` (Part A §A.7), filling the field-level shapes of the `beamNode`, `beamBranch`, `opticalSystem`, `layer`, and `unitOfMeasure` `$defs` (owned by Part A). FSharp.SystemTextJson MUST be used for DU/record/option serialization (Part A storage seam). The domain project model — including the beam tree — MUST NOT be serialized with FsPickler/`.binz` (Part A constraint 4); `.binz` via `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize`/`BinaryZippedFormat` (`C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Core.fs:254,257`) is reserved for derived/bulk sidecars and is out of scope for Part B. Thicknesses and wavelengths in the JSON MUST be the canonical SI values (meters), with human units applied only at the UI/IO boundary (Part A constraint 3).

Scope exclusion: schema versioning, autosave, recent-files, and undo/redo persistence ([Standard], 010 §7) are out of scope for Part B; only the field-level shapes of the listed `$defs` are filled here.

### R-10 (B.10) The construction page MUST commit the operator-facing UX for destructive structural edits

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` introduces the top-level construction/stack-and-tree page with destructive operations (delete layer, delete branch/sub-tree, detach mirror reflected child), so it MUST commit explicitly on the operator UX checklist:

1. **Discoverability/nav entry.** The construction page MUST be a top-level navigation entry in the main shell, reachable without opening a dialog, and MUST be the default landing surface for a newly opened or newly created project.
2. **Progress granularity.** Per-node solve invoked from this page (§B.1) MUST surface a busy indicator at node granularity; because a single flat-element solve is short, the page MUST NOT block the whole tree while one node recomputes. Long sweeps/optimizations are owned by other parts and are out of scope here.
3. **Pre-confirmation gate vs one-click.** Deleting a layer row MUST be one-click with undo (item 5); deleting a beam node that has attached children (a sub-tree) MUST present a pre-confirmation gate naming the count of descendant nodes that will be removed, re-derived live from the tree (no stale count).
4. **Completion→results refresh.** After any structural edit (add/delete/reorder/duplicate/group a layer, attach/detach a branch, toggle substrate, change a medium), the affected sub-tree MUST be re-solved and the dependent schematic/results views MUST refresh from the new `EmFieldSystem` (§B.1) without a manual reload.
5. **Opposing-action UX + undo.** Every destructive structural action (delete, detach) MUST have an opposing add/attach action in the same toolbar, and a single-level undo MUST restore the immediately prior immutable tree/`films` snapshot (the model is immutable per §B.2/§B.5, so undo is a prior-value swap, not a mutation reversal). Multi-level undo/redo history ([Standard], 010 §7) is owned by Part I (§I.6).
6. **Committable file vs root `.gitignore`.** The JSON project file written by §B.9 is a committable user artefact and MUST default to the project's working folder, not the repository root; Part B MUST NOT write derived `.binz` sidecars from the construction page (those are out of scope here, §B.9).

### R-11 (B.11) Gradient-index / inhomogeneous layers MUST auto-discretize into reused `Layer` sub-layers [Standard]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) MUST realise 010 §1's [Standard] "Gradient-index / inhomogeneous layers auto-discretized into sub-layers" (010 lines 123-124) as a pure expansion that turns one continuously-varying-index layer into an ordered list of homogeneous reused `Layer` records (`Media.fs:24`). This part MUST add a net-new record `GradientLayer = { totalThickness : double<meter>; subLayerCount : int; indexProfile : double<meter> -> OpticalProperties }` and a pure function `discretize : GradientLayer -> Layer list` that slices `totalThickness` into `subLayerCount` equal `Thickness.Thickness` sub-layers (`Media.fs:12`), each carrying the `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`) sampled from `indexProfile` at that sub-layer's mid-depth. The produced sub-layers MUST be ordinary `Layer` records indistinguishable from manually entered ones — exactly the flat-`Layer`-list discipline `RepeatBuilder.expand` follows (Part J §J.2) — and MUST be assignable straight into `OpticalSystem.films` (`Media.fs:98`); this part MUST NOT introduce a new gradient-layer engine type, MUST NOT discretize at solve time inside the solver, and MUST NOT store the unfactored profile in the canonical JSON (only the expanded `films` persist, per §B.9). `subLayerCount` MUST be a required argument validated `>= 1` through the Part J §J.9 validation seam; thicknesses MUST remain `double<meter>` (Part A canonical-units rule). Adaptive/error-driven sub-layer refinement is OUT OF SCOPE — the count is caller-supplied, uniform slicing only.

## Non-requirements

- The `BeamTree`/`BeamNode`/`BeamBranch`/`ConstructorElement`/`BeamTreeError` type definitions are owned by Part A (slice 001); this slice fills the construction/solver-driving/propagation logic, the mirror-attach enforcement body, and the default-unit hook.
- The `UnitOfMeasure` DU and conversion functions are owned by Part D (slice 002); the hook (B.8) only stores a `UnitOfMeasure` value and MUST NOT implement conversions.
- Curved elements (`Lens`/`CurvedMirror` local-interface physics, zone fan, grading) are owned by Part C (slice 004); Part B classifies `FlatMirror` only.
- The materials library, dispersion resolution, and index→tensor construction are owned by Part D (slice 002); medium selectors consume a resolved `OpticalProperties`.
- The repeat/period builder (J.2), multi-level undo/redo (I.6), live-recalculation caching, sweeps/charting, and the J.9 validation seam implementation are out of scope (owned by Parts J/I/F).
- The serialization seam (`serializeProject`/shared options) and schema scaffold are owned by Part A (slice 001); this slice fills only the field-level physics `$defs` for the beam tree.

